  ---
  Section 2 — The Two PageIndex Instances

  Legal DB PageIndex — Pre-computed, Static

  Built once offline. Updated only when laws are amended.

  Structure per node:
  {
    "node_id": "BNS-103",
    "title": "Section 103 — Murder",
    "act": "Bharatiya Nyaya Sanhita 2023",
    "section_number": "103",
    "old_equivalent": "IPC Section 302",
    "summary": "Whoever commits murder shall be punished with death or imprisonment for life...",
    "keywords": ["murder", "culpable homicide", "death penalty"],
    "sub_nodes": [...],
    "page_range": [88, 89]
  }

  The old_equivalent field is critical — lawyers still think in IPC numbers, the system silently maps BNS/BNSS.

  Pre-computation strategy:
  - Parse all bare acts (BNS, BNSS, BSA, Constitution, etc.) as PDFs/text
  - For each section, generate a 2-3 sentence LLM summary (one-time cost)
  - Build the tree bottom-up: sections → chapters → acts → full DB
  - Store as JSON + MongoDB for fast node_id lookups
  - Estimated size: ~50,000 nodes across all 11 domains
  - One-time compute: ~4-6 hours with GPT-4.1 for summaries, then static forever

  Client Docs PageIndex — Per-case, Dynamic

  Built when a case is created/documents uploaded. Cached by case_id.

  {
    "case_id": "CASE-2024-001",
    "document": "FIR_dated_2024-03-15.pdf",
    "doc_type": "FIR",
    "node_id": "CASE-2024-001-FIR-P3",
    "title": "FIR Page 3 — Statement of Complainant",
    "summary": "Complainant states accused entered premises at 11pm...",
    "page": 3,
    "sub_nodes": [...]
  }

  Built on upload → cached → reused for every query in that case session.

  ---
  Section 3 — Summarizer + Router (What They Actually Do)

  These two work as a pipeline gate before anything expensive runs:

  Raw Client Doc
        ↓
  [Summarizer] — model: BERT-based or LLM with prompt
        ↓ outputs:
        ├── Extractive summary (top sentences, not paraphrased)
        ├── Entities: names, dates, locations, amounts
        ├── Legal sections mentioned ("Section 420 IPC" → maps to BNS 318)
        └── Doc type: FIR / contract / affidavit / judgment

        ↓ all above feeds into ↓

  [Router / Multi-label Classifier]
        ↓ outputs:
        ├── Domain labels: ["criminal", "constitutional"] with confidence
        ├── Primary domain (highest confidence) → main adapter
        └── Secondary domains → supporting adapters (if confidence > 0.4)

  Router implementation options (pick based on your timeline):

  ┌────────────────────────────────────┬────────────┬──────────┬───────────────┐
  │               Option               │ Complexity │ Accuracy │     Speed     │
  ├────────────────────────────────────┼────────────┼──────────┼───────────────┤
  │ Rule-based (keyword matching)      │ Low        │ ~70%     │ Instant       │
  ├────────────────────────────────────┼────────────┼──────────┼───────────────┤
  │ Zero-shot big model classification │ Low        │ ~85%     │ 1-2s API call │
  ├────────────────────────────────────┼────────────┼──────────┼───────────────┤
  │ Fine-tuned BERT classifier         │ Medium     │ ~92%     │ 50ms local    │
  ├────────────────────────────────────┼────────────┼──────────┼───────────────┤
  │ Fine-tuned on InLegalBERT          │ High       │ ~95%     │ 50ms local    │
  └────────────────────────────────────┴────────────┴──────────┴───────────────┘

  Recommendation: Start with zero-shot big model classification (ship fast), replace with fine-tuned BERT once you have labelled data
  from real usage.

